{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
He'd [F]eat a country ham and he’d [C]enjoy the fat
He'd [F]take a hard boiled egg and [C]put it in his [G7]hat
He'd ask to [C]mow your lawn in a tone of woe
You know he'd [G7]never work this lonesome [C]poor hobo
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
His shoes were always worn sometimes they wouldn't match
His hat was [G7]always flopped his clothes were [C]always patched
He had the finest watch on the finest chain
He'd keep the [G7]closest time on the [C]fastest train
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
I've [F]seen him catch a freight the [C]best in the land
I've [F]seen him grab a train with a [C]sandwich in his [G7]hand
He saw [C]all the world but never made no dough
And died a [G7]happy man his name was [C]Lonesome Joe
{end_of_verse}





